WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.720
Hello, everyone. Do you hear me well? Yeah, cool. Hola. So I'm going to talk to you about

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:16.280
the development of the datos package that's part of the R4DataScience translation. So

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:22.520
this talk is about how it's to be an R user when English is not your first language. So

00:00:22.520 --> 00:00:27.040
we have to acknowledge that there's a language gap, that people that doesn't speak English

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:33.119
or that are not very proficient in English, that can be a very difficult thing to do.

00:00:33.119 --> 00:00:38.040
So for example, when you try to learn something new, you want to insert some data into a vector

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:44.560
and want to learn how to use the append function, you may run into this resource, the R cookbook.

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:49.919
So you want to learn how to use this function, and you have this whole context that explains

00:00:49.919 --> 00:00:55.000
you how to use it. But when English is not your first language and you're not very proficient,

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:59.360
that context doesn't exist at all. So you have to try to figure out how to understand

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:03.759
that function without the context, and sometimes that can be very difficult.

00:01:03.759 --> 00:01:11.400
So someone may ask, why don't you just learn English? That will be much easier. Okay. Well,

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:16.320
that's a possibility. But for many people, learning English is a privilege. The country

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:22.959
where I came from, I live in Chile, one level of an English course can cost you like $500,

00:01:22.959 --> 00:01:28.599
but the minimum wage is $350. So it's not only costly, but we also have to think it's

00:01:28.599 --> 00:01:33.720
time consuming. So you want to learn R. So why I have to learn English first and then

00:01:33.720 --> 00:01:41.000
learn R, that's not the idea. So happy R users like me want that everybody learns R. So sometimes

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.519
we have dreams like this one, for example, have R for data science translated to Spanish

00:01:45.519 --> 00:01:50.160
and have R for data science. So O'Reilly, you can help us.

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:55.480
So the story I'm going to tell you starts in 2017, and as many stories in the R community,

00:01:55.480 --> 00:02:02.040
it started on Twitter. So Hadley Wickham announced that R for data science was going to be translated

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:07.599
into Chinese, French, Korean, Portuguese, Russian, Serbian. Cool. So Marcella Alfaro

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:13.320
from the Costa Rican R community asked, well, what about Spanish? And Hadley said, strangely,

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:19.240
no. And that's very strange, because Spanish is the language that had the second most amount

00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:27.520
of native users, so there's a lot of Spanish-speaking R users that want to read this.

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:35.360
So in 2018, Edgar Ruiz from RStudio, he forked the original repository and decided to start

00:02:35.360 --> 00:02:39.559
the translation, but he didn't do nothing at all, because this is very difficult to

00:02:39.559 --> 00:02:45.600
do, translate a book. So he needed a community, and he was alone in this. And a couple of

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:51.160
months later, at our OpenSciConf, Laura asked, Hadley, what about the translation? And he

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:55.199
said, no, it's not going to happen. O'Reilly is not interested in Spanish. But you can

00:02:55.199 --> 00:03:00.800
do it if you want. So she spread the news around the RLadies network and on Twitter,

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:05.000
and the next week, we have the first conference call between all the people that were interested

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:12.160
in this project. And just two days after the video conference, we have our X sticker, because,

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:18.479
you know, if you don't have an X sticker, you're not a real R project. So we became

00:03:18.479 --> 00:03:22.759
a sticker-driven project. We have a team of stickers, so we can start.

00:03:22.759 --> 00:03:30.279
So everyone started forking the repository, and 21 people were involved in the translation

00:03:30.279 --> 00:03:36.039
from different backgrounds, from different countries, and we have another around 30 people

00:03:36.039 --> 00:03:42.000
that review those translations. So this was about a 50-people effort project. So all these

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.240
people speak different varieties of Spanish, which is very useful, because you don't want

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:51.279
to be rude. You know, translated something in some way, and that's very offensive in

00:03:51.279 --> 00:03:56.759
another part of Latin America. People from different backgrounds. There were people that

00:03:56.759 --> 00:04:01.880
were from statistics, from biology, from social science, from the humanities. Also people

00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:06.800
with different R experience, experts and novices, and people with different GitHub

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:12.800
experience, and this was very risky, because we forked the repository and the people forked

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:19.440
our fork, so you have around 30 people trying to manage how to contribute.

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:23.679
So in this first conference, we decided two things. First, that we want to translate the

00:04:23.679 --> 00:04:30.640
text and the datasets that are used in the book, because they're useful not only for

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:36.359
the book, but for teaching R, and also which infrastructure we were going to use. So we

00:04:36.359 --> 00:04:42.040
used mainly GitHub and Slack. In GitHub, we have our fork of the book, we have our repository

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:48.679
with all the documentation of the project, and the repository for the package. And we

00:04:48.679 --> 00:04:56.079
have responsibilities. Edgar was leading the development of the package, but I was involved

00:04:56.079 --> 00:05:03.399
with taking care that we didn't break the repository, and I was involved with the translation

00:05:03.399 --> 00:05:08.040
and coordinating the whole process. So GitHub is very useful for translation, because you

00:05:08.040 --> 00:05:14.799
can have both versions of the text, and reviewers can put comments in between, so they can make

00:05:14.799 --> 00:05:20.359
suggestions how to improve the translation. And Slack was also very useful, well, we can

00:05:20.359 --> 00:05:26.519
organize this, but also because of polls, because we have to make many decisions about

00:05:26.519 --> 00:05:32.320
how we are going to translate some stuff. For example, we have empty cars. We have to

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:36.559
translate the cars, and we can say cars in three different ways in Spanish. So we have

00:05:36.559 --> 00:05:43.920
to decide autos, coches, or carros. So autos won, and now we have emete autos.

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:48.799
And there's some other very difficult stuff to decide. For example, we have the pipe,

00:05:48.959 --> 00:05:53.679
and in Spanish, all nouns have a grammatical gender, so we have to decide if the pipe was

00:05:53.679 --> 00:05:59.679
going to be masculine or feminine. So we made a poll, and everyone voted that the pipe was

00:05:59.679 --> 00:06:06.239
masculine, except me, because for me the pipe was a she. So now I have to change my mind

00:06:06.239 --> 00:06:12.119
about how I thought about the pipe. So we decided that we want to translate the

00:06:12.119 --> 00:06:18.200
text and the datasets, and for the text, there were previous experiences that were very helpful.

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:26.279
For example, the Carpentries has translated some lessons to Spanish, and they have this

00:06:26.279 --> 00:06:33.440
guide with the agreements about how they are translating technical words, so we get inspired

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:39.480
about that. And also the Programming Historian, it's a website where we publish peer-reviewed

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:44.239
tutorials that help people from the humanities to learn digital tools, and has a version

00:06:44.239 --> 00:06:49.480
in Spanish and French. So there are, like, guidelines for reviewers, for translation,

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:54.519
for authors, and that was very useful to get inspired by that.

00:06:54.519 --> 00:06:58.600
And what about the dataset? There were two possible approaches. What we wanted is, for

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:04.359
example, we have the diamonds dataset, we want diamantes, and we wanted to have, like,

00:07:04.359 --> 00:07:10.000
the variable translated and the name of the different values. And one possible approach

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:17.500
was just to, for example, rename the variables and then translate the name of the values.

00:07:17.500 --> 00:07:22.880
But another approach was using Datalang, a package that Edgar Ruiz developed, that has

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:29.640
this function that's called translated data, that takes a YAML file with the translation,

00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:34.980
the specification for the translation, and as a result, you get your dataset translated.

00:07:34.980 --> 00:07:41.500
So how it works, you have this YAML file, so you put which is the source packet, the

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:46.420
original dataset in English, how it's going to be named in Spanish, you specify how you

00:07:46.420 --> 00:07:53.459
want to translate the variables, for example, price became precio, and the description.

00:07:53.459 --> 00:07:59.179
You also explain which values you want to translate it, and you also translate the help.

00:07:59.179 --> 00:08:06.579
So you have documentation in Spanish also. So you not only get the dataset translated,

00:08:06.579 --> 00:08:14.179
but also you get the help page for the dataset. So that's very useful for people who are learning.

00:08:14.179 --> 00:08:19.739
So this approach of translating the book and the dataset using this packet make very easy

00:08:19.739 --> 00:08:24.019
to contribute, because you can participate in a packet just by knowing how to edit a

00:08:24.019 --> 00:08:28.179
YAML file. So last year, when we were developing the

00:08:28.179 --> 00:08:35.700
packet, we sent a proposal to Luz, but the packet wasn't finished, so it became a conference-driven

00:08:35.700 --> 00:08:43.500
packet. We have to finish it before the conference. So we were working fine, but when we decided

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:48.299
to send the packet to Crown, we realized it was too bulky, because we have a packet with

00:08:48.299 --> 00:08:53.780
a lot of datasets inside. So what we decided to do was that the dataset translate on the

00:08:53.780 --> 00:08:59.780
fly. So actually the translated datasets are not in the packet. In the packet, you only

00:08:59.780 --> 00:09:05.419
find the YAML files. So we have these two functions that translate the data on the fly.

00:09:05.419 --> 00:09:10.619
Once you call, for example, diamantes, it goes to find the YAML translated dataset and

00:09:10.619 --> 00:09:16.140
offer you the translated version. So that makes the packet much lighter.

00:09:16.140 --> 00:09:19.900
So we were very happy with that, but one day we were trying to do something, and we

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:26.219
realized we were not able to call the dataset that way, and we were, like, very stuck and

00:09:26.219 --> 00:09:31.500
hardly remember that this function exists, delayed assign, and that helped us to solve

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:38.179
that. So now you can call the data packet whichever way you want.

00:09:38.179 --> 00:09:49.500
So we are in Crown now. Edgar was leading the development of the packet, and I helped

00:09:49.500 --> 00:09:55.940
with the whole process, and also people from the community got involved. And where we are

00:09:55.940 --> 00:10:01.619
now, the datasets are all translated. The code, we had to edit all the code from the

00:10:01.619 --> 00:10:06.780
book, because it has, like, the original datasets. The translations are ready, and the reviews

00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:15.619
are ready. So we have, like, the first complete version of the book in ES.R for DS. So now

00:10:15.619 --> 00:10:21.820
we have this first version that people can use to learn R.

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:27.059
And there was a thing we had to decide. What about the edition? Because we want this book

00:10:27.059 --> 00:10:32.979
to be updated every time. So I decided that a good idea is to watch the repository. So

00:10:32.979 --> 00:10:39.299
every time they change something in the repository, I can edit it back to the book. And one day,

00:10:39.299 --> 00:10:48.859
January 15, I woke up, and I had to collapse my inbox with 42 messages, because they decided

00:10:48.859 --> 00:10:54.520
that that was the day to update all the pull requests that were in the repository.

00:10:54.520 --> 00:11:02.580
So I thought I was able to be a conference-driven editor, but I failed, so I'm still, like,

00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:07.299
making the last changes. So is this really the end of the project,

00:11:07.299 --> 00:11:12.500
now that the book is ready? This started in 2018, but I think it's a project that will

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:17.659
last forever, because what we have created is not just a translation and a book package.

00:11:17.659 --> 00:11:22.659
What we created was human and technical infrastructure to shorten the language gap that currently

00:11:22.659 --> 00:11:26.260
exists. And I think our big contribution, developing

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:32.340
the data package, was creating brand-new errors, because people now, if they fail using

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:41.059
the package, they are not going to find, like, ways to solve it alone. But I think this is

00:11:41.059 --> 00:11:47.719
an opportunity, because failing is a way to make our community stronger.

00:11:47.880 --> 00:11:49.880
So thank you very much.

00:11:49.880 --> 00:11:51.880
APPLAUSE

00:11:59.400 --> 00:12:06.280
So once again, if you'd like to ask a question, we use the app, app.sli.do. We have one question

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:12.400
here. Have you seen an increase in Spanish-speaking R users since the release of the package?

00:12:13.359 --> 00:12:21.280
Yes, I think so. We put the book online from the beginning, so you can start, like, using

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:27.479
the chapters. Some of them were translated very fast. So, yeah, there are many people

00:12:27.479 --> 00:12:32.919
that are using the package to teach, so it has now a live outside-the-book translation.

00:12:32.919 --> 00:12:39.799
Fabulous. That's the only question we have. Well, please, thank you.

00:12:39.799 --> 00:12:41.799
APPLAUSE

00:12:42.400 --> 00:12:44.799
Thank you.

